{
  "comment_text": {
    "sn2.8:1.2": "Tāyana means “defender” (here the affix <i lang='pi' translate='no'>-ana</i> is agentive). Compare Vedic <i lang='pi' translate='no'>trātṛ</i>, “defender”, an epithet of Indra (eg. Rig Veda 2.23.8, 6.25.7). ",
    "sn2.8:2.1": "These verses are often recited by mendicants to remind them of their commitment. ",
    "sn2.8:2.4": "As, for example, the gods of universal beauty (<a href='https://suttacentral.net/an7.44/en/sujato#4.1'>AN 7.44:4.1</a>). Tāyana taught rebirth in the Brahmā realm as the goal of his spiritual life, as did other religious founders of the past (<a href='https://suttacentral.net/an6.54/en/sujato'>AN 6.54</a>, <a href='https://suttacentral.net/an7.73/en/sujato'>AN 7.73</a>, <a href='https://suttacentral.net/an7.74/en/sujato'>AN 7.74</a>, <a href='https://suttacentral.net/an7.66/en/sujato'>AN 7.66</a>). "
  },
